    Search instead for Strawberry fugicides options

    An AI Overview is not available for this searchCan't generate an AI overview right now. Try again later.
    AI Overview
    Effective strawberry fungicide options include broad-spectrum protectants like Captan, Thiram, and sulfur, along with systemic options for specific diseases. Key products for Botrytis gray mold and anthracnose include Switch, Elevate, Pristine, Luna Sensation, and Miravis Prime. Rotate between FRAC groups to prevent resistance. 
    Key Fungicide Options by Disease & Type 
    • Botrytis Gray Mold: Switch, Elevate, Captevate, Scala, and Pristine.
    • Anthracnose: Captan, Switch, Luna Sensation, Miravis Prime, and Abound.
    • Powdery Mildew: Mettle, Torino, Quintec, and sulfur.
    • Root Rot/Phytophthora: Mefenoxam (Ridomil Gold).
    • Organic Options: Copper-based fungicides (e.g., copper hydroxide or oxychloride) and bio-fungicides like OSO. 
    Application and Management Tips 
    • Resistance Management: Rotate fungicides with different FRAC codes (e.g., switching between FRAC 7, 9, 11, and 12) to prevent resistance development.
    • Timing: Apply during 510% bloom and again at full bloom, particularly during wet seasons.
    • Coverage: Ensure high-volume spray penetration, especially for dense canopy or crown issues.
    • Pre-Harvest Interval (PHI): Always check labels, though some products like Mettle 125 ME allow for a 0-day PHI. 
    For severe issues like Neopestalotiopsis, use a rotation of fungicides including Switch, Thiram, or Echo.

    Can you spray 24D on strawberries?
    While commonly used herbicides such as glyphosate cannot safely be applied directly over the strawberry plants, it can be spot-applied to kill stubborn weeds near the rows. Avoid using 2,4-D in strawberries except during renovation and according to label instructions.

    How to get rid of fungus on strawberries?
    Use fungicide sprays, if necessary.

    Apply a fungicide at 510% bloom and at full bloom. Fungicides may be reapplied every 710 days during wet seasons. Pesticides registered for use include captan, chlorothalonil, copper, iprodione, mancozeb, sulfur, thiram, and ziram.

    Do strawberries like mycorrhizal fungi?
    A number of studies have reported the beneficial effects of mycorrhiza on strawberry plants (Castellanos-Morales et al., 2010) and commercial AMF inoculum has been shown to increase both growth (crowns, roots and leaf area) and tolerance to water stress in micro-propagated strawberry (Borkowska, 2002).Aug 19, 2016
